## Context
Two quick wins that should ship together. Both live in the message render component.

## Part 1: sanitizeStreamingMarkdown()
Create a utility function that makes partial markdown safe to render mid-stream by closing unclosed syntax constructs.

**Location:** `apps/ui/src/lib/streaming-markdown.ts`

```ts
export function sanitizeStreamingMarkdown(text: string): string {
  // Close unclosed fenced code blocks
  const fences = (text.match(/```/g) || []).length;
  if (fences % 2 !== 0) return text + '\n```';

  // Close unclosed inline code
  const backticks = (text.match(/(?<!`)`(?!`)/g) || []).length;
  if (backticks % 2 !== 0) return text + '`';

  // Close unclosed bold
  const boldMarkers = (text.match(/\*\*/g) || []).length;
  if (boldMarkers % 2 !== 0) return text + '**';

  return text;
}
```

Export and unit test with Vitest: unclosed fence, unclosed inline code, unclosed bold, clean input (no-op).

## Part 2: Plugin array memoization fix
Find all usages of react-markdown in `apps/ui/src/` and ensure remarkPlugins and rehypePlugins arrays are hoisted to module scope (not inline).

**Wrong:**
```tsx
<ReactMarkdown remarkPlugins={[remarkGfm]}>
```

**Correct:**
```tsx
const REMARK_PLUGINS = [remarkGfm]; // module scope

<ReactMarkdown remarkPlugins={REMARK_PLUGINS}>
```

Inline array refs cause react-markdown to remount the full component tree on every token update.

Fix all occurrences. No new files needed beyond the utility.

## Acceptance Criteria
- `sanitizeStreamingMarkdown` exported from `apps/ui/src/lib/streaming-markdown.ts`
- Unit tests pass for all 4 cases
- Zero inline `remarkPlugins={[...]}` or `rehypePlugins={[...]}` in the codebase
- TypeScript compiles clean

